        "order": 41
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-j.1365-2117.2002.00179.x.pdf_10_41",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Basinward horizontal distance (km)",
        "bbox": [
          0.3818201681570032,
          0.4505177626320253,
          0.6284450310955998,
          0.4624131732302958
        ],
        "order": 42
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-j.1365-2117.2002.00179.x.pdf_10_1",
        "observed_type": "caption",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Fig. 10. Reconstructed shoreline trajectories. Note that the trajectories for vi = 0.45 ÷ 0.10 km show concave-basinward geometry.",
        "bbox": [
          0.1273101056333077,
          0.47668650773848587,
          0.9117042942297992,
          0.4883720929572485
        ],
        "order": 43
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-j.1365-2117.2002.00179.x.pdf_10_42",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Vi = 0.45 $ 0.10 km, however, the trend of steady increase in S is still retained. With yi = 0.45 km, the magnitude of S in the middle stage, when the shelf edge was located somewhere between sites P-M, is three times as large as in the initial stage. In the latest stage, furthermore, the magnitude of S became over 14 times as large as in the initial stage. A significantly different trend of S is seen with Vi ≥ 0.70 km: S decreases in the early stage and then increases later. It is an important point that, whatever magnitude Vi took, S tended to become highest at the latest stage, when the shelf edge was migrating from site M to site D.",
        "bbox": [
          0.1252566729602479,
          0.5086805555378872,
          0.5092402469576166,
          0.6627906977002549
        ],
        "order": 44
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-j.1365-2117.2002.00179.x.pdf_10_46",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Polygons 1p, Um, and nd in the x-y plane represent the spatial distribution of any possible adv, that was obtained from the data sets measured at sites P, M, and D, respectively. The degree of overlap between polygons is expressed as pm (for overlap between Mp and Am) and PMD (for overlap between My and ND) (see Eq. (11)).",
        "bbox": [
          0.5359342910300632,
          0.5086805556347864,
          0.9199178640007377,
          0.5930232554575801
        ],
        "order": 45
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-j.1365-2117.2002.00179.x.pdf_10_47",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "There is no overlap between up and Am (i.e. PpM = 0) when Vi ≤ 0.35 km and vi ≥ 1.05 km. With yi = 0.40-1.00 km, on the other hand, up and Am overlap each other (i.e. 0 < PpM < 1). However, the highest value of PpM (at yi = 0.40 km) is as low as 0.137. Excluding the cases that Vi =0.40-0.45 km, the overlap is negligible (PpM ~ 0). On the other hand, the overlap of My and ND is in a significantly different trend from that between 1p and Mm. There is some overlap between Am and nD (0 < PMD) when yi = 0.20-0.90 km. At any magnitude of vi within this range, PuD is much larger than that of ppm (Fig. 14). The highest values of PMD (0.55-0.60) are seen when y; = 0.50 0.70 km. With Vi = 0.45 ÷ 0.10 km, PMD ranges between 0.31 and 0.55, still much larger than the highest of PM.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5338809100837931,
          0.5930059522289366,
          0.9220446247682175,
          0.7921626982499023
        ],
        "order": 46
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-j.1365-2117.2002.00179.x.pdf_10_43",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The pattern of changing A, opposite to that of changing S (Eq. (10)), is shown in Fig. 12 in the form of a relative sealevel curve. When Vi takes a low magnitude (e.g. 0.05-0.20 km), the relative sea-level change is characterized with a rapid rise in the early stage followed by a slow rise or nearly a standstill in the late stage. This trend is also seen in the case of y; = 0.45 ÷ 0.10 km. When y; = 0.80 km, there was no change in A while the shelf edge was prograding from site i to site M. With yi ≥ 0.85 km, the relative sealevel curve is sigmoidal in shape where the highest magnitude of A is realized between sites P and M.",
        "bbox": [
          0.1252566729602479,
          0.6641865080399635,
          0.5092402453576851,
          0.8183139534223647
        ],
        "order": 47
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-j.1365-2117.2002.00179.x.pdf_10_49",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The clear monomodal distribution of 'successful' runs (Fig. 9) suggests that the initial water depth (Vi) for the shelf-edge progradation is most likely to have been around 0.45 km. Less attention needs to be paid to other",
        "bbox": [
          0.5359342926299945,
          0.8357558141052831,
          0.9219712531177808,
          0.8909883719735107
        ],
        "order": 49
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-j.1365-2117.2002.00179.x.pdf_10_44",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Assessment of the uncertainty",
        "bbox": [
          0.127310070122394,
          0.8430059521697066,
          0.3100615992136769,
          0.85319767421836
        ],
        "order": 50
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-j.1365-2117.2002.00179.x.pdf_10_45",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The results of the analyses of the uncertainty of the field data and related assumptions are shown in Figs 13 and 14.",
        "bbox": [
          0.1252566729602479,
          0.8633432538164592,
          0.5092402341581646,
          0.889632936655397
        ],
        "order": 51
      }
    ]
  },
